page_functionality.state_logic:
On page load, the client reads URL parameters query, category, max_read_time, view, and page. If view equals 'reading_list', the page enters reading list mode: it calls getReadingListArticles, displays the reading list component, and does not call searchArticles. In this mode, query, category, max_read_time, and page parameters do not affect the loaded data, although they may be preserved in the URL for when the user switches back to search mode.

If view is absent or set to any value other than 'reading_list', the page enters search mode. It constructs a filters object for searchArticles using any present category and max_read_time parameters. It sets the current search page from the page URL parameter if present; otherwise the first page is used. It then calls searchArticles with the following arguments:
- query: taken directly from the query URL parameter (or left empty if absent);
- filters: an object that includes category and max_read_time if those URL parameters are present;
- page: derived from the page URL parameter or defaulted to the first page when page is missing or reset after filter changes;
- page_size: determined by application-level configuration or user selection, not hardcoded in this specification.

Whenever the user performs an action that changes search state (submitting a new query, changing category, adjusting max_read_time, clearing filters, or selecting a different page), the page updates the corresponding URL parameters and then re-invokes searchArticles with argument values derived from the updated URL. This ensures that the URL is always a complete representation of the current search state and can be shared or revisited to reproduce the same set of results.

When the user toggles to reading list view via the UI, the page updates the URL by setting view=reading_list and loading articles.html in that mode. When toggling back to all articles, the view parameter is removed or set to a non-reading-list value; the page then enters search mode and calls searchArticles using the remaining URL parameters (query, category, max_read_time, page). No state is stored in localStorage; state is fully derived from the URL and the responses of getArticleCategoryOptions, searchArticles, and getReadingListArticles.
